   {:e #blake3 "11ed292226a46975bd4cae8e43887f331093de80631c423d2893f8372dfd2482" :a :harvest/accomplishments :v "Session entity: :recon/trace-305a427a751109f1; Session entity: :task/t-290097c8; Session entity: :task/t-c076efe6; Session entity: :task/t-6e606e1e; Session entity: :task/t-3c66d0c1; Session entity: :recon/trace-6199894957ee2ce5; Session entity: :recon/trace-a763510e210d0d21\nCCE LIFECYCLE WIRING PROPOSAL: Wire the 8 dead kernel functions into the CLI at two integration points. INTEGRATION POINT 1 — OBSERVE (on concept join): When assign_to_concept returns Joined, the CLI must: (a) Compute surprise_weight(surprise, alpha) from the assignment. (b) Call update_centroid_weighted(old_centroid, old_total_weight, obs_embedding, weight) to get new centroid. (c) Write updated :concept/embedding (new centroid), :concept/member-count (increment), :concept/total-weight (accumulate), :concept/variance (recompute from centroid distance). These datoms go in the SAME CCE follow-up transaction. The concept is now a LIVING entity that evolves with each observation. INTEGRATION POINT 2 — HARVEST (crystallize uncategorized): At harvest time, after collecting harvest candidates: (a) Find all observations with :exploration/embedding but WITHOUT :exploration/concept (uncategorized). (b) Collect their embeddings and body texts. (c) Call crystallize_concepts(observations, JOIN_THRESHOLD, MIN_CLUSTER_SIZE). (d) For each NewConcept: call concept_to_datoms + membership_datoms, write to store. (e) Report: '3 new concepts crystallized: event-processing, error-handling, deployment'. New emergent concepts then participate in future assign_to_concept calls. This IS the ontology discovery loop. INTEGRATION POINT 3 — STATUS (lifecycle checks): After concept_inventory: (a) For each concept with variance > SPLIT_THRESHOLD, recommend split: 'concept:X may need splitting (variance=0.63)'. (b) For each pair with should_merge, recommend merge: 'concepts X and Y are highly similar (cosine=0.91)'. These are RECOMMENDATIONS, not automatic actions — the agent decides. VERIFICATION: (A) After 5 observations about 'event sourcing', the event-related innate concept shows member_count=5 (not 0). (B) After 10 diverse observations, harvest crystallizes at least 1 new concept. (C) braid status shows accurate member counts, not static zeros. (D) Surprise-weighted centroids shift toward surprising members.; Session entity: :task/t-c792bc33; Session entity: :task/t-6f1f81b6; CRITICAL DISCOVERY: CCE pipeline is 50% dead code. Eight kernel functions — crystallize_concepts, update_centroid, update_centroid_weighted, concept_to_datoms, membership_datoms, should_split, should_merge, surprise_weight — are NEVER called from the CLI. The observe command writes :exploration/concept Ref and :exploration/surprise datoms when an observation matches a concept, but NEVER updates the concept itself: no centroid update, no member-count increment, no total-weight accumulation, no variance recomputation. The harvest command NEVER calls crystallize_concepts — new concepts cannot form from uncategorized observations. The status command NEVER calls should_split/should_merge — concepts cannot restructure. CONSEQUENCE: The CCE is a static concept LOOKUP against the 5 innate schemas, not a learning system. Concepts never grow, evolve, split, merge, or emerge. The entire CCE-2 (concept formation), CCE-2b (surprise-weighted centroids), and the developmental trajectory (sensorimotor → concrete operational → formal operational) are spec-complete in the kernel but unwired in the CLI. This is not a hash-embedder-vs-model2vec problem. Even with perfect semantic embeddings, the system would assign observations to static innate concepts but never: (1) update the concept centroid to reflect new members, (2) form new emergent concepts from clusters of uncategorized observations, (3) split concepts that become too broad, (4) merge concepts that converge. The SEMANTIC-EMBED EPIC addresses the FIRST bottleneck (concept assignment quality). This discovery reveals the SECOND bottleneck: concept lifecycle is completely unwired." :op :assert}
